{"cursor":"4763","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox royalty\n| type = monarch name = Alfonso IV image = Alfonso IV de Leon.jpg imgw = 200px\n| caption = succession = King of LeÃ³n reign = 925â931 coronation = predecessor =\n| Fruela II successor = Ramiro II spouse = Oneca SÃ¡nchez of Pamplona issue =\n| OrdoÃ±o IV Fruela issue-link = issue-pipe = house = Beni Alfons house-type\n| = Dynasty father = OrdoÃ±o II of LeÃ³n mother = Elvira Mendes birth_date =\n| birth_place = death_date = August 933 death_place = Monasterio de Ruiforco\n| burial_place = Basilica of San Isidoro religion = Roman Catholicism }}\n\n'Alfonso IV' (c. 890s â 933), called 'the Monk', was King of LeÃ³n from 925 (or\n926) and King of Galicia from 929, until he abdicated in 931.\n\nWhen OrdoÃ±o II died in 924 it was not one of his sons who ascended to the throne\nof LeÃ³n but rather his brother Fruela II of Asturias. The exact circumstances of\nthe succession upon Fruela's death one year later are unclear, but the son of\nFruela, Alfonso FrÃ³ilaz, became king in at least part of the kingdom. Sancho\nOrdÃ³Ã±ez, Alfonso, and Ramiro, the sons of OrdoÃ±o II, claimed to be the rightful\nheirs and rebelled against their cousin. With the support of king Jimeno GarcÃ©s\nof Pamplona, they drove Alfonso FrÃ³ilaz to the eastern marches of Asturias, and\ndivided the kingdom among themselves with Alfonso OrdÃ³Ã±ez receiving the crown of\nLeÃ³n and his elder brother Sancho being acclaimed king in Galicia.\n\nAlfonso IV resigned the crown to his brother Ramiro in 931 and went into a\nreligious house. One year later he took up arms with Fruela's sons OrdoÃ±o and\nRamiro against his own brother Ramiro, having repented of his renunciation of\nthe world. He was defeated, blinded, and sent back to die in the cloister of\nSahagÃºn. Alfonso had married Oneca SÃ¡nchez of Pamplona, niece of his ally Jimeno\nGarcÃ©s and daughter of Sancho I of Pamplona by Toda of Navarre. He had two\nchildren: OrdoÃ±o IV of LeÃ³n, and perhaps another son, Fruela, who was involved\nin a land dispute during the reign of Ramiro III of LeÃ³n. A minority of\nmodern scholars including Claudio SÃ¡nchez-Albornoz and Manuel Carriedo Tejedo,\nconsider OrdoÃ±o IV instead to have been son of his rival Alfonso FrÃ³ilaz.\nIndependently, the placement of the Froylani prolis Adefonsi regis (Fruela, son\nof king Alfonso) of the time of Ramiro III as son of king Alfonso IV rather than\nking Alfonso FrÃ³ilaz has been disputed.\n","linknr":169,"url":"Alfonso_IV_of_León","recorded":1375075537,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Alfonso_IV_of_Le%C3%B3n&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Alfonso_IV_of_Le%C3%B3n&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:Translation_to_english_arrow.svg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Translation_to_english_arrow.svg/50px-Translation_to_english_arrow.svg.png","//es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfonso_IV_de_Le%C3%B3n","//es.wikipedia.org/wiki/","http://translate.google.com/translate?&u=http%3A%2F%2Fes.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FAlfonso+IV+de+Le%C3%B3n&sl=es&tl=en","/wiki/Talk:Alfonso_IV_of_Le%C3%B3n","/wiki/Wikipedia:Copying_within_Wikipedia","/wiki/Wikipedia:Translation","/wiki/File:Alfo